  <h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Decode DOCG vs DOC Quality Levels</strong> - Prosecco di Conegliano e Valdobbiadene DOCG represents the pinnacle, with steeper vineyards producing wines with more pronounced minerality and complex pear-apple fruit. Standard Prosecco DOC covers a vast area and offers lighter, more approachable styles. The price difference (often 2-3x) reflects genuine terroir advantages: DOCG zones' calcareous soils and cooler temperatures create wines with better structure and aging potential of 3-5 years versus DOC's immediate consumption window.</li>

  <li><strong>Brut vs Extra Dry Sweetness Strategy</strong> - Despite the name, "Extra Dry" Prosecco (12-17g/L residual sugar) is actually sweeter than "Brut" (0-12g/L). Choose Brut for aperitifs and shellfish pairings where you want crisp acidity to shine. Extra Dry works better with spicy Asian cuisine or fruit-based desserts where the slight sweetness balances heat and acidity. Dry styles (17-32g/L) from producers like Bisol are excellent with blue cheese.</li>

  <li><strong>Vintage vs Non-Vintage Performance Window</strong> - Vintage Prosecco (Millesimato) from exceptional years like 2020 or 2019 develops honeyed notes and nuttier complexity after 2-3 years, making them worth cellaring briefly. Non-vintage blends are designed for immediate pleasure and lose their fresh pear-citrus character after 18 months. Store vintage bottles at 50-55°F and consume non-vintage within one year of purchase for optimal fruit expression.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve Temperature Precision by Style</strong> - Basic Prosecco DOC performs best at 40-42°F to maximize its fresh apple-pear character, while premium DOCG wines benefit from slightly warmer serving (44-46°F) to allow mineral complexity and subtle almond notes to emerge. Over-chilling premium Prosecco masks the terroir-driven nuances you're paying extra for. Use an ice bucket for 15 minutes rather than refrigerator storage for optimal temperature control.</li>

  <li><strong>Glassware Impact on Bubble Structure</strong> - Flute glasses preserve the fine, persistent mousse that distinguishes quality Prosecco, but tulip-shaped glasses (like Riedel's Prosecco-specific glass) better showcase aromatic intensity in premium bottlings. Avoid wide coupe glasses with any Prosecco - they dissipate both bubbles and aromatics too quickly. The narrow opening concentrates the delicate white flower and citrus zest aromatics that separate good Prosecco from industrial versions.</li>

  <li><strong>Producer Reputation Hierarchy</strong> - Family estates like Nino Franco, Bisol, and Adami consistently deliver superior fruit selection and longer lees aging (2-3 months vs. minimum 30 days) that creates creamier mousse. Large industrial producers often use shorter tank time and higher yields, resulting in simpler fruit profiles. Look for "sui lieviti" on labels - this indicates extended lees contact that adds textural richness worth the premium price.</li>

  <li><strong>Cartizze vs. Standard Terroir Recognition</strong> - Prosecco from Cartizze, a 267-acre grand cru zone within Valdobbiadene, commands premium pricing for good reason: the steep, south-facing slopes and unique microclimate produce grapes with higher natural acidity and more concentrated mineral character. These wines develop elegant white peach and acacia honey notes unavailable in broader DOCG zones. Expect to pay 40-60% more, but the distinctive chalky minerality and aging potential justify the investment for special occasions.</li>

  <li><strong>Cork vs. Crown Cap Quality Indicators</strong> - Traditional cork closures in Prosecco often indicate longer aging potential and premium positioning, while crown caps (like beer bottles) are used for fresher, immediate-consumption styles. However, some quality producers like Ca' del Bosco use crown caps specifically to preserve primary fruit character. The key is matching closure to drinking timeline: cork-finished Prosecco for cellaring 1-3 years, crown caps for drinking within 6-12 months of release.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Unlike many still wines, prosecco's aging potential varies dramatically across quality tiers, making proper storage decisions crucial for maximizing your investment.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Style</h3>
<p><strong>Prosecco DOC</strong> wines should be consumed within 2-3 years of purchase, as their fresh fruit character—driven by primary fermentation esters like ethyl acetate—begins to fade rapidly. <strong>Prosecco DOCG</strong> from Conegliano Valdobbiadene can develop beautifully for 3-5 years, particularly single-vineyard bottlings where mineral complexity emerges as citrus notes evolve into honey and almond nuances.</p>

<p><strong>Franciacorta DOCG</strong> represents the pinnacle of aging potential, with vintage releases capable of 8-12 years of cellaring. The extended lees aging (minimum 18 months) creates autolytic compounds that provide structure for long-term development.</p>

<h3>Storage Requirements</h3>
<p>Store prosecco bottles <strong>upright</strong> in a consistent 50-55°F environment with 60-70% humidity. Unlike cork-sealed wines, the crown cap or synthetic closure maintains carbonation without requiring horizontal storage. Avoid temperature fluctuations above 60°F, which accelerate the breakdown of CO₂ and compromise mousse quality.</p>

<h3>Evolution and Peak Windows</h3>
<p>Properly aged prosecco develops secondary characteristics: fresh apple transforms into baked pear, while floral notes become honeyed. Premium Conegliano Valdobbiadene wines reach peak complexity at 3-4 years when fruit intensity balances with developing mineral complexity.</p>

<h3>Recognizing Proper Aging vs. Spoilage</h3>
<p>Well-aged prosecco maintains bright acidity with evolved fruit flavors and persistent bubbles. Warning signs include: browning color (oxidation), musty aromas (cork taint in traditional method wines), or flat texture indicating CO₂ loss. Sediment in vintage Franciacorta is normal after 5+ years, while any sediment in young Prosecco DOC suggests refermentation issues.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between Prosecco DOCG and DOC classifications?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Prosecco DOCG (like Conegliano Valdobbiadene and Asolo) represents the highest quality tier, made exclusively from Glera grapes grown in specific hillside vineyards with stricter production rules. DOC Prosecco covers a much larger area across Veneto and Friuli, allowing for higher yields and less stringent quality controls, typically resulting in wines that are lighter and less complex than their DOCG counterparts.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do Extra Brut, Brut, and Extra Dry Prosecco options compare in sweetness?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Extra Brut Prosecco contains 0-6 grams of residual sugar per liter, offering bone-dry crispness that pairs beautifully with oysters and sushi. Brut (6-12g/L) provides subtle fruit sweetness while maintaining food-friendly acidity, making it the most versatile option. Extra Dry (12-17g/L) delivers noticeable sweetness that complements spicy Asian cuisine and works well as an aperitif with light appetizers.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which Prosecco producers offer the best value under $20?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Mionetto Prosecco DOC delivers consistent quality with bright citrus notes and fine bubbles for around $12-15. Villa Sandi Il Fresco offers excellent value at $15-18 with its clean minerality and delicate pear flavors from sustainable vineyards. For premium quality under $20, look for Bisol Jeio Prosecco di Valdobbiadene DOCG, which provides the complexity of hillside fruit at an accessible price point.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I choose tank method or traditional method sparkling wine over Prosecco?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Prosecco's tank method (Charmat) preserves fresh fruit flavors and floral aromatics that make it perfect for casual drinking and lighter fare. Traditional method sparkles like Champagne or Franciacorta offer more complexity, toastiness, and aging potential but at significantly higher prices. Choose Prosecco when you want bright, approachable bubbles for everyday enjoyment, and traditional method when celebrating special occasions or pairing with richer foods.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when selecting Prosecco?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is choosing Prosecco based solely on price without considering the sweetness level and intended use. Many people grab Extra Dry thinking it's the driest option, when it actually contains more residual sugar than Brut. Always check the label for sweetness designation and match it to your preference—Brut for food pairing and dry palates, Extra Dry for those who prefer a touch of sweetness.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long should I chill different Prosecco styles before serving?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Basic DOC Prosecco needs 3-4 hours in the refrigerator to reach the ideal 38-42°F serving temperature that showcases its fresh fruit character. Premium DOCG Prosecco benefits from slightly warmer serving (42-46°F) to allow complex mineral and floral notes to emerge, requiring about 2-3 hours of chilling. Never serve Prosecco too cold (below 35°F) as it mutes the delicate aromatics that distinguish quality producers.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can you age Prosecco, or should all styles be consumed young?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Most DOC Prosecco is designed for immediate consumption within 1-2 years of release to preserve its signature fresh fruit and floral characteristics. However, premium Prosecco Superiore DOCG from top producers like Nino Franco or Adami can develop beautiful honeyed complexity over 3-5 years when stored properly. Vintage-dated Prosecco and Rive designations have the most aging potential, while non-vintage bottles should be enjoyed for their youthful vibrancy.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What alternatives to Italian Prosecco offer similar styles at different price points?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Spanish Cava provides excellent value with similar freshness and food-friendly acidity, typically priced 20-30% less than comparable Prosecco. American sparkling wines from producers like Gruet or Schramsberg offer tank-method options with bright fruit character and competitive pricing. For a step up, consider Franciacorta DOCG, which uses traditional method production but maintains the fresh, elegant style that Prosecco lovers appreciate, though at Champagne-level prices.</p>
  </div>
</div>

